===Etymology===
A jocular coinage, apparently by pupils at [[w:Eton College|Eton]], combining a number of roughly synonymous Latin stems. The word was inspired by a line in the ''Eton Latin Grammar'' that listed verbs that govern a genitive noun: "Flocci, nauci, nihili, pili, assis, hujus, teruncii, his verbis, aestimo, pendo, facio, peculiariter adduntur."<ref>''The Spectator'': 11 June 2011</ref>  {{etyl|la|en}} ''flocci'', from ''[[floccus]]'', a wisp or piece of wool + ''nauci'', from ''[[naucum]]'', a trifle + ''nihili'', from the {{etyl|la|en}} pronoun, {{term|nihil||nothing|lang=la}} + ''pili'', from ''[[pilus]]'', a hair, something insignificant (all therefore having the sense of "pettiness" or "nothing") + [[-fication]].

